The Social Conditioning of Fear

Authors

Alejandra Pedraza

W. Jamie Yang

Abstract
TBW

Introduction

Individualsâ report of fear have been shown to relate to a wide range of contextual factors, such as neighborhood composition and community crime rates (Hale 1996; Warr 1990), and individual sociodemographic characteristics, such as gender, sexual orientation, income, age, health condition, and immigration status (LaGrange and Ferraro 1989; Otis 2007; Madriz 2023). To be more specific, this body of scholarship has found spatial and neighborhood characteristics have a significant impact on individualsâ self-reported fear of crime, as those who live in areas with high levels of community disorder have reported more fear than those who do not live in such communities (Rountree and Land 1996). Also, due to the popularity density in urban areas, residents of these areas have reported higher levels of fear at night, potentially because of feelings of alienation and unfamiliarity among residents (Bennett and Flavin 1994).

Especially, the role of gender in fear of crime has been well documented in victimization research (Cops and Pleysier 2011; Snedker 2006; Schnitzer et al. 2010; Elizabeth A. Stanko 1993). Early scholarship emphasized that women tend to report more fear than men (Elizabeth Anne Stanko 1990), with some initial research investigating the seeming disjuncture between womenâs fear and their actual experiences of victimization, as women were often found to report high levels of fear for crimes that they were at relatively little risk of experiencing (Hough, Mayhew, et al. 1983). Subsequent studies suggested that womenâs fear should be understood in the context of the many potential threats that women confront, including their heightened risk of sexual assault (Elizabeth A. Stanko 1993). Therefore, fear at night is gradually perceived as a manifestation of gender-based violence with sexual assault implications, though acknowledging that sexual assault is merely one among many potential forms of crime. However, the more insidious and everyday forms of harassment are frequently not captured by common survey instrumentsâ-they regularly privilege the more obvious or extreme forms of victimization and fail to account for the routine forms of violence that women confront (Moran et al. 2003). We focus our attention on this less intrusive but omnipresent form of everyday violence and examine the unequal effects it has on different populations. We ask: what groups of people are more likely to have experienced fear of walking alone at night in their neighborhood?

Historically, despite all the aforementioned contexts and individual-level characteristics being identified as salient to individualsâ self-reported fear at night, they were usually studied in isolation. Notably, scholars have tended to focus either on individual-level characteristics, such as race and sexual orientation, or on physically defined contexts like schools and neighborhoods and social contexts like networks, families, with little consideration of the joint contributions of multiple contexts and multilevel effects simultaneously. To fill this gap in knowledge, we hypothesize that, similar to âthe social determinants of healthâ (Krieger 2001), there exist the social determinants of fearâ-intersectional social positionalities impact the likelihood of individualsâ sense of threat from social surroundings, i.e., fear at night.

This is an exploratory project for a dissertation chapter idea that one of the co-authors wants to pursue. With descriptive statistics, we are interested in investigating the inequalities in terms of fear of walking alone at night among the US adult population and mapping out the patterns of disparities along the axes of race, gender, sexual orientation, citizenship status, and education. We use the 2022 data from the General Social Survey (GSS) and the data science tools from EDLD 651 class to delineate the data distribution and basic correlations between âfear of walkign alone at nightâ and our other variables of interest.

Methods

This study draws data from the General Social Survey (GSS). The GSS is a nationally representative interview-based survey that has collected longitudinal data since 1972. The GSS contains questions on demographics, behaviors, attitudes, civil liberties, crime and violence, intergroup tolerance, morality, national spending priorities, psychological well-being, social mobility, stress, and traumatic events. Our study is limited to data collected during the 2022 wave and we draw primarily on demographic and well-being variables.

Our dependent variable is coded as fear by the GSS. Respondents were asked, âIs there any area right around hereâthat is, within a mileâwhere you would be afraid to walk alone at night?â During the 2022 wave, there were 3,544 answers coded as follows: 878 = yes, 1440 = no, and 1226 = NA. Notably, the GSS codes missing values with multiple indicatorsââ.i: Inapplicable,â â.n: No answer,â â.d: Do not Know/Cannot Choose,â and â.s: Skipped on Web.â For the purposes of our preliminary study, we coded all missing data as NA. Furthermore, we applied fixed removal of NAs for our dependent variable and we ran mice imputations for all other variables to create a more robust dataset that is necessary for further modeling.

Our control and independent variables are representative of two different dimensions we sought to capture. The first dimension is individual-level or social identity characteristics:

  • born: Were you born in this country?

  • age: Respondentâs age in numeric values.

  • sexnow1: Do you describe yourself as male, female, or transgender?

  • sexornt: Which of the following best describes you? [1] âGay, lesbian, or homosexualâ [2] Bisexual [3] Heterosexual or straight [99] âRefusedâ

  • racerank1: If you had to choose, which of these races do you identify most with?

  • hispanic: Are you Spanish, Hispanic, or Latino/Latina? IF YES: Which group are you from?

  • degree: Respondentâs (highest educational) degree.

  • uscitzn: Are you a US citizen?

  • dwelown: (Do you/Does your family) own your (home/apartment), pay rent, or what?

Informed by theory, race is an important co-variate for our models as racialization serves to structure the daily lives of individuals based on where they fall on the Black-white spectrum, their opportunities, and their sense of belonging (Bonilla-Silva 2022; Omi and Winant 2015). First, we sought to create a combined race variable from the variables race and hispanic. After looking at the data, we saw that race was coded as âBlack, White, or Other.â This does not provide the control we need as it omits those in the âracial middleâ that are more likely to identify with a panethnic label and reject the Black-white binary (Mora 2014; OâBrien 2008; Rodriguez 2000). Instead, we opted to use the racerank1 variable, because participants were able to select from 16 different options: White, Black or African-American, Asian Indian, Chinese, Filipino, Japanese, Korean, Vietnamese, Other, Asian, Guamanian or Chamorro, Samoan, Other Pacific Islander, Some other race, and Hispanic. We factored and recoded these to White, Black, Hispanic, Asian, NHPI (Native Hawaiian or Pacific Islander), AIAN (American Indian, Alaska Native), and Other. We understand that these categories are problematic and contentious (Haney-LÃ³pez 2006; Dowling 2014), however they are the standard with quantitative data.

Similarly, gender was a contentious variable to account for. Although the GSS has several questions aimed at capturing respondentâs gender, we found them to be lacking in breadth. For example, the GSS codes sex within a Male/Female binary based solely on interviewer discretion. Ultimately, we opted to use sexnow1 since it was the variable that most closely captured self-described gender. However, it remains problematic as respondents were only provided four choice: Male, Female, Transgender, and None of these. Out of 2306 cases, only 10 were coded as Transgender and 9 as None of these. Therefore, this is by no means a representative sample on gender minority population. The fact that the GSS data is primarily collected through in-person field interviews increases the possibility that minority-identifying individuals may not disclose their accurate identity information to avoid being associated with negative stereotypes.

Another important variable we sought to control for was citizenship status, since citizenship status and the associated stigma of illegality and threat of deportation have been found to increase fear in daily life (Golash-Boza 2015; Kline 2019). However, GSS data is not conducive to controlling for this variable due to the large number of NAs. Out of 2318 cases, 2164 were coded as NAs. In future work, we will pursue data options that allow the analysis ton include citizenship status.

The second dimension we sought to capture was community-level characteristics that would potentially affect oneâs sense of safety. For this dimension, we drew on the following variables:

  • attend: How often do you attend religious services?

  • raclive: Are there any (âwhitesâ for black respondents, âblacksâ for non-black respondents) living in this neighborhood now?

These variables seek to account for respondentâs social embeddedness and networks of support. Specifically, raclive is an important variable to consider as it accounts for neighborhood composition, in the absence of a neighborhood dissimilarity index. While this variable only looks at Black-white racial composition, it provides a good benchmark to examine broader racial antagonisms. Research has documented the associated fears white experience when Blacks or people of other racial backgrounds move into their neighborhood (Lacayo 2017; Massey 2020).

The third dimension we considered were individual-level health-related and attitudinal variables. Good mental and physical health status is positively correlated with individualsâ evaluation of their life conditions and affects how likely individuals are to report positive emotions about their life (Dwyer-Lindgren et al. 2017). Additionally, social capitalâ-such as levels of interpersonal trust and norms of reciprocity and mutual aidâis believed to play an important role in explaining variations in health status across geographic localities (Kawachi 1999). Therefore, we included the following variables that capture respondentsâ self-reported health status and assessment of interpersonal social climate:

  • happy: Taken all together, how would you say things are these daysâwould you say that you are very happy, pretty happy, or not too happy?

  • health: Would you say your own health, in general, is excellent, good, fair, or poor?

  • helpful: Would you say that most of the time people try to be helpful, or that they are mostly just looking out for themselves?

  • fair: Do you think most people would try to take advantage of you if they got a chance, or would they try to be fair?

  • trust: Generally speaking, would you say that most people can be trusted or that you canât be too careful in dealing with people?

  • partnrs5: since February/March 2015, and including the past 12 months, how many sex partners have you had in that five year period?

Data Script

Code 
gss <- import(here("data", "GSS.xlsx")) %>%
  as_tibble() %>% 
  clean_names()
Code 
gss2022 <- gss %>% 
  filter(year == "2022")
Code 
data <- gss2022 %>% 
    select(age, sex, sexnow1, sexornt, degree, attend, raclive, happy, health, helpful, fair, trust, fear, partnrs5, racerank1, uscitzn, dwelown)
Code 
missing_vec <- c(".i:  Inapplicable", ".n:  No answer", ".d:  Do not Know/Cannot Choose", ".s:  Skipped on Web")
    
tidydata <- data %>% 
  mutate(across(c(age, sex, sexnow1, sexornt, degree, attend, raclive, happy, health, helpful, fair, trust, fear, partnrs5, racerank1, uscitzn, dwelown), 
                ~ifelse(. %in% missing_vec, NA_character_, .)))
Code 
tidydata <- tidydata %>% 
  filter(!is.na(fear)) %>% 
  mutate(age = as.numeric(age)) %>% 
  mutate(raclive = as.factor(raclive)) %>% 
  mutate(sexnow1 = as.factor(sexnow1)) %>% 
  mutate(fear = factor(case_when(fear == "NO" ~ "no",
                                 fear == "YES" ~ "yes"))) %>% 
  mutate(racecombo = 
           factor(case_when(racerank1 == "White" ~ "White",
                     racerank1 == "Black or African-American" ~ "Black",
                     racerank1 == "Hispanic" ~ "Hispanic",
                     racerank1 == "Asian Indian" | racerank1 ==  "Chinese" |
                       racerank1 ==  "Filipino" | racerank1 ==  "Japanese" | 
                       racerank1 ==  "Korean" |  racerank1 ==  "Vietnamese" |
                       racerank1 ==  "Other Asian" ~ "Asian",
                     racerank1 == "American Indian or Alaska Native" ~ "AIAN",
                     racerank1 == "Guamanian or Chamorro" | racerank1 == "Samoan" |
                       racerank1 == "Other Pacific Islander" ~ "NHPI",
                      racerank1 == "Some other race" ~ "Other"))) %>% 
  mutate(racecombo = fct_relevel(racecombo, 
              "White",
              "Black", 
              "Asian",
              "Hispanic",
              "AIAN",
              "NHPI",
              "Other")) %>%   
  mutate(partnrs5 = 
           factor(case_when(partnrs5 == "NO PARTNERS" ~ "0",
                            partnrs5 == "1 PARTNER" | partnrs5 == "2 PARTNERS" |
                              partnrs5 == "3 PARTNERS" | 
                              partnrs5 == "4 PARTNERS" ~ "Less than 5",
                            partnrs5 == "5-10 PARTNERS" ~ "5-10",
                            partnrs5 == "11-20 PARTNERS" ~ "11-20",
                            partnrs5 == "21-100 PARTNERS" ~ "21-100",
                            partnrs5 == "MORE THAN 100 PARTNERS" ~ "100 or more",
                            .default = NA))) %>%
  mutate(partnrs5 = fct_relevel(partnrs5,
                                "0",
                                "Less than 5",
                                "5-10",
                                "11-20",
                                "21-100",
                                "100 or more")) %>%
  mutate(uscitzn = 
           factor(case_when(uscitzn == "A u.s. citizen" | uscitzn == "A u.s. citizen born in puerto rico, the u.s. virgin islands, or the northern marianas islands (if volunteered)" |
                       uscitzn == "Born outside of the u.s. to parents who were u.s. citizens at that time (if volunteered)" ~ "Yes",
                     uscitzn == "Not a u.s. citizen" ~ "No",
                     .default = NA))) %>% 
   mutate(dwelown =
           factor(case_when(dwelown == "Own or is buying" ~ "Owner",
                            dwelown == "Pays rent" ~ "Renter",
                            dwelown == "Other" ~ "Other"))) %>% 
  mutate(degree = fct_relevel(degree, 
                              "Less than high school",
                              "High school",
                              "Associate/junior college",
                              "Bachelor's",
                              "Graduate")) %>% 
  mutate(attend = fct_relevel(attend, 
                              "Never",
                              "Less than once a year",
                              "About once or twice a year",
                              "2-3 times a month",
                              "Nearly every week",
                              "Every week",
                              "Several times a week")) %>% 
  mutate(happy = fct_relevel(happy, 
                             "Not too happy",
                             "Pretty happy",
                             "Very happy",)) %>% 
  mutate(health = fct_relevel(health, 
                              "Poor",
                              "Fair",
                              "Good",
                              "Excellent")) %>% 
  mutate(helpful = fct_relevel(helpful, 
                               "Looking out for themselves",
                               "Try to be helpful",
                               "Depends")) %>% 
  mutate(fair = fct_relevel(fair, 
                            "Would take advantage of you",
                            "Would try to be fair",
                            "Depends")) %>% 
  mutate(trust = fct_relevel(trust, 
                             "Can't be too careful",
                             "Can trust",
                             "Depends"))
Code 
gss_subset <- tidydata %>% 
  select(age, sexnow1, racecombo, uscitzn, degree, attend, raclive, happy, health, partnrs5, fear)
Code 
overall_fear <- gss_subset %>% 
  mutate(fear = case_when(fear == "no" ~ "0",
                                 fear == "yes" ~ "1")) %>% 
  select(fear)
mean_fear <- mean(as.numeric(overall_fear$fear, na.rm=TRUE))
Code 
complete5 <- mice(gss_subset, 
                 m = 5, 
                 seed = 25)

temp5 <- complete(complete5, action = "long", include = TRUE)

Results

In the absence of running models, in this section we will discuss descriptive statistics through a series of tables and plots. We seek to show how the experience of fear differed across different measures of individual-level and community-level characteristics. To begin with, across our sample of 2318 cases, mean fear was calculated at 0.3787748. One thing to note about the interpretation of this value is, because we operationalized the variable fear as a dichotomous variable with answers being âYes = 1â and âNo = 0â, this mean value approximates âthe likelihood for an individual in our sample to report the experience of fear of walking alone at night in their neighborhoodâ.

First, we examined how fear is experienced across race and gender. As TableÂ 1 shows, Transgender and Female respondents had higher mean fear rate than respondents who identified as Male. Particularly, respondents that were Transgender expressed greater fear, but this may be indicative of sample representation. For example, only one respondent identified as both Hispanic and Transgender, and since they responded affirmative to the question, this finding is heavily skewed. When looking by race, whites were the group with the lowest mean fear and Asians were the group with the highest. This finding is consistent with the hypothesis that the most privileged social group in terms of race has the lowest level of fear.

Code 
gss_subset %>% 
  filter(!is.na(racecombo)) %>% 
  filter(racecombo != "Other") %>% 
  filter(!is.na(sexnow1)) %>% 
  filter(sexnow1 != "None of these") %>% 
  pivot_longer(
    cols = fear,
    names_to = "fear",
    values_to = "answer") %>% 
  select(racecombo, answer, sexnow1) %>% 
  mutate(fear = as.numeric(case_when(answer == "no" ~ "0",
                                 answer == "yes" ~ "1"))) %>% 
  select(racecombo, fear, sexnow1) %>% 
  group_by(racecombo, sexnow1) %>% 
  summarize(mean_fear = mean(fear)) %>% 
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = sexnow1,
    values_from = mean_fear
  ) %>% 
  kable(caption = "Social Fear by Race and Gender",
        col.names = c("Race", "Female", "Male", "Transgender"),
        digits = 3) %>% 
  kableExtra::row_spec(0:6, background = "white")

Code 
gss_subset %>% 
  filter(!is.na(racecombo)) %>% 
  filter(racecombo != "Other") %>% 
  filter(!is.na(sexnow1)) %>% 
  filter(sexnow1 != "None of these") %>% 
  group_by(racecombo, sexnow1) %>% 
  summarize(fear = sum(fear == "yes"), 
            n = n(),
            prop = fear/n) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = racecombo, y = prop)) +
  geom_col(aes(fill = sexnow1), position = "dodge") + 
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Purples") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  labs(title = "Social Fear by Race and Gender",
       subtitle = "Is social fear influenced by respondent's race and gender?",
       x = "Race",
       y = "Percentage of Respondents who Expressed Fear") +
  theme_bw() +
  guides(fill = guide_legend(title = "Gender"))

Moving on to measures of social embeddedness, we examined fear across degrees of religious participation, degree of happiness and health, residential diversity, and sexual activity. Regarding religious participation, we did not discern any clear pattern, as FigureÂ 2 displays below.
